    "rationale": "This reaction shows the reduction of a simple, acyclic ketone (butan-2-one) to the corresponding alkane (n-butane) using hydrazine (NN) and potassium hydroxide ([OH-].[K+]), which are the classic reagents for the Wolff-Kishner reduction. The transformation is a clear deoxygenation of a carbonyl group to a methylene group, which is the defining feature of this reaction. The substrates and products are small, acyclic, and lack complex functional groups, making it a clear and unambiguous example.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "This example uses a simple aliphatic ketone to avoid overlap with reactions involving aromatic systems (like Friedel-Crafts acylation/alkylation) or other functional groups. It is distinct from the Clemmensen reduction, which uses acidic conditions (Zn(Hg)/HCl), and from reductions of other functional groups. The simplicity of the substrate focuses the query specifically on the carbonyl-to-methylene transformation characteristic of the Wolff-Kishner reduction."
